This behavior occurs both in nest relief and when a bird comes back to the nest.

name: Major Mitchell's Cockatoo

When raised, it can indicate a number of intentions: displaying for its mate; calling its flock members; defending its flock or territory; or expressing curiosity, excitement, fear surprise, or frustration. funfact: Herons have good sight and can hunt at night, as well as during the day.

funfact: In the early 1600s, Rock doves were introduced to North America.

funfact: This species is the largest in its genus (Diomedea) and one of the worldâ€™s largest birds.

funfact: The Gouldian finch was described by British ornithological artist John Gould in 1844 as 'Amadina gouldiae', in honor of his wife Elizabeth.

funfact: The Peregrine falcon is the world's most widespread raptor, and one of the most widely found bird species.

name: Saker Falcon

funfact: Crested caracaras sometimes follow trains or cars to collect food that falls from them.
name: Crested Caracara

funfact: Magnificent frigatebirds spend days and night on the wing, with an average ground speed of 10 km/h (6.2 mph), covering up to 223 km (139 mi) before landing. The only other bird known to spend days and nights on the wing is the Common swift.

Males always lift up their wings over their backs during the unison calling, while females keep their wings folded at their sides. The male initiates this display and produces one call for each responding female call.

funfact: The French Queen Marie Antoinette named this bird for its delicate appearance.

funfact: The whooping crane has a smooth and stately gait, while its courtship dance is a display of leaping, kicking, wing-sweeping and head pumping.

funfact: These birds often put their whole head under water when feeding.

funfact: Though the species has the name Red-crowned crane, it does not, in fact, belong to the crowned crane family but to the species of typical crane.

funfact: When brolga babies are threatened, they hide and keep quiet while the parent performs a broken-wing display to lure the predator away.

funfact: Common grackles are known to practice "anting" behavior; they rub insects on their feathers possibly to apply liquids such as formic acid secreted by the insects in order to get rid of parasites.

funfact: Although named a "cowbird," this species does not look like a cow but got its name because it followed herds of bison on North Americaâ€™s Great Plains, eating insects kicked up by the cattle.
name: Brown-Headed Cowbird

funfact: Bobolinks travel about a 12,500-mile round-trip each year, being amongst the longest migrations undertaken by any songbird from the New World. To navigate across this vast distance, it is thought that they use the Earthâ€™s magnetic field and the positions of the stars.
name: Bobolink

funfact: In 1825, a nephew of Napoleon Bonaparte, Charles Lucien Bonaparte, first described the Yellow-headed blackbird, a specimen of which had been collected by Sir John Richardson and Thomas Say in 1820.

funfact: Red-winged blackbirds use their beaks to open a seed, catch a fly, spear a beetle or crack open an acorn.

funfact: This species was first described by Carolus Linnaeus, in 1758, a Swedish physician, botanist and zoologist.

funfact: The genus name the Black-headed gull Chroicocephalus comes from Ancient Greek khroizo - "to colour", and kephale - "head".

funfact: A Royal tern defecates directly onto the rim of its nest, perhaps to reinforce it against flooding, as in a few weeks, the rim of the nest hardens.

funfact: Fairy tern adults and chicks, as well as eggs in nests, are camouflaged so well that you can pass by them without even knowing.
name: Fairy Tern

funfact: Hatching out, chicks of terns usually have 2 colors - brown and gray â€“ while they occasionally have different colors, even coming from one family.
name: Arctic Tern

funfact: Tern behavior includes an event known as â€˜dreadâ€™ which is usually early in the breeding season, when all or most of the terns suddenly fly up from the ground to scoop low over the colony site or the sea, to deter predators or apparently for no reason.
name: Common Tern

funfact: The call of the least tern is a high-pitched â€œzeep", "zreep,â€ or â€œkit.â€
name: Least Tern

funfact: The genus name â€˜Sternaâ€™ comes from the Old English "stearn", "tern", The specific "dougallii is after the Scottish collector and physician Dr Peter McDougall (1777â€“1814).
name: Roseate Tern

funfact: The red beak, red legs and characteristic white moustache of an Inca tern do not develop until they reach 1-2 years old.
name: Inca Tern

funfact: The Sooty tern together with the Gray-backed tern are known collectively as â€œmanutaraâ€. Manutara played an important part in the tangata manu or "birdman" ritual.
name: Sooty Tern

funfact: White terns make a repeated guttural â€œheech-heechâ€. At the nest site they are usually silent.
name: White Tern

funfact: Like other species of fairywrens, Splendid fairywrens may use a 'rodent-run' display to distract predators from nests with chicks. While doing this, the head, neck, and tail of the bird are lowered, the wings are held out and the feathers are fluffed as the bird runs rapidly and voices a continuous alarm call.
name: Splendid Fairy-Wren

funfact: Superb fairy-wrens always forage in groups and this is very helpful; this way insects that were disturbed by one bird may be caught by another.
name: Superb Fairy-Wren

funfact: The Green bee-eater has a distinguishing predator-avoidance behavior, in that if a potential predator looks at the birdâ€™s nest, the Green bee-eater will not enter it until the predator looks away. This remarkable behavior shows that the bird is aware of what the predator is looking at, but also suggests awareness of a predatorâ€™s mental state. This â€˜theory of mindâ€™ awareness is typically only part of human behavior and several other primate species.
name: Green Bee-Eater

funfact: The Gray catbirdâ€™s syrinx (being a double instrument located where the trachea separates into two bronchi) is unusual in that both sides can operate independently, meaning that they are able to sing using two voices at the same time.
name: Gray Catbird

funfact: Helmeted guineafowl have been widely introduced into the West Indies, Brazil, Australia, and Europe.
name: Helmeted Guineafowl

funfact: A group of bobwhites is known as a "covey", "bevy", and "name dropping" of bobwhites.
name: Northern Bobwhite

funfact: Gambelâ€™s quail are excellent and fast runners. These birds rarely fly, being slow in flight. For this reason, they mainly remain on the ground, running if necessary.
name: Gambel's Quail

funfact: The hoatzin is the only member in its genus Opisthocomus; the word 'opisthocomus' comes from Ancient Greek and means 'wearing long hair behind' which refers to the bird's large crest.
name: Hoatzin

funfact: Crested bellbirds are also called 'Dick-Dick-the Devil' because of their call.
name: Crested Bellbird

funfact: A Great bustard in flight often is named â€œflying fortressâ€ because of being the worldâ€™s heaviest flying bird. Its flight is majestic and powerful, the bird beating its wings slowly and regularly.
name: Great Bustard

funfact: Unlike other birds, Kori bustards lack a preen gland, instead producing a powder down, allowing them to keep clean. In addition, the birds often sunbathe as well as dust bathe.
name: Kori Bustard

funfact: At the right time of year, it is not difficult to observe male birds-of-paradise enact their magical courtship display because they return to the same trees to do it. Dozens of males may arrive at one tree, and some of them use the same trees generation after generation.
name: Greater Bird-of-Paradise

funfact: Certain New Guinea tribes use bird-of-paradise plumes as currency.
name: King Bird-of-Paradise

funfact: The name "Wilsonâ€™s" is used because Napoleonâ€™s nephew used this name for an unknown bird that had been purchased by the British naturalist Edward Wilson. In doing this, he beat John Cassin by several months, who had wanted to name this species in honor of Wilson. In 1863, 13 years later, Heinrich Agathon Bernstein, the German zoologist discovered on Waigeo Island the home of the Wilson's bird-of-paradise.
name: Wilson's Bird-of-Paradise

funfact: A Black-capped chickadee often hides berries and seeds under leaves or in the crevices of bark, and is able to remember these locations for as long as a month.
name: Black-Capped Chickadee

funfact: â€˜Pelecaniformesâ€™ is the family that pelicans belong to, being distinguished from other birds because all 4 of their toes are webbed, known as â€˜totipalmateâ€™.
name: Great White Pelican

funfact: Brown pelicans, after bathing, use their beaks to spread oil from the uropygial gland over their feathers.
name: Brown Pelican

funfact: Pelicans incubate eggs using their webbed feet, as they lack bare skin on their belly, known as a â€œbrood patchâ€.
name: American White Pelican

funfact: The Australian pelicans have an extremely light skeleton, which weighs only 10% out of the whole weight of their body and allows them to fly.
name: Australian Pelican

funfact: The Dalmatian pelicans use their throat pouch not only to capture fish but also as a cooling mechanism. They open their beaks during hot weather, pulsating their pouch in order to speed up the rate of cooling by evaporation.
name: Dalmatian Pelican

funfact: â€˜Cormorantâ€™ comes from the Latin 'corvus marinus', meaning 'sea crow'.
name: Great Cormorant

funfact: Like other smallish cormorants, the Pelagic cormorant is sometimes called the Pelagic shag.
name: Pelagic Cormorant

funfact: The Double-crested cormorantâ€™s crest is visible only on adults during the breeding season. It is white for cormorants from Alaska, but black for those in other regions.
name: Double-Crested Cormorant

funfact: The feathers of Flightless cormorants are not waterproof.
name: Flightless Cormorant

funfact: The Himalayan monal is the national bird of Nepal, where it is known as the danphe or danfe.
name: Himalayan Monal

funfact: The Ruffed grouse is the state bird of Pennsylvania, United States.
name: Ruffed Grouse

funfact: The tail of the male Red junglefowl can grow up to 28 centimeters (11 in) and contains 14 feathers.
name: Red Junglefowl

funfact: During the winter, the birds prepare for the approaching breeding season, gaining weight and strength by eating sagebrush leaves and getting required moisture from the snow.
name: Greater Sage Grouse

funfact: Gunnison sage-grouse communicate by calls, courtship vocalizations, and signaling with their feathers. Calls can be used for defending territory or to signal a threat to others.
name: Gunnison Sage-Grouse

funfact: Amongst flamingos, only the Andean flamingo has yellow legs and feet.
name: Andean Flamingo

funfact: Flamingos are considered the world's most beautiful tall birds.
name: James's Flamingo

funfact: Flamingos come from an ancient bird group. Their fossil record goes back about 10 million years, to the Miocene epoch.
name: Chilean Flamingo

funfact: Greater flamingos produce a loud goose-like honking call, 'ka-haunk'.
name: Greater Flamingo

funfact: Lesser flamingos are very noisy; their call during flight is a high-pitched sound, kwirrik. When walking or feeding they make a low murmuring murrrh-murrrh-errh. Lesser flamingos are excellent swimmers.
name: Lesser Flamingo

funfact: The American flamingo, like all flamingos, is a noisy bird. Its voice plays an important part in keeping the flock together. Sounds vary according to the type of activity, usually low gabbling while feeding, and nasal honking during flight. Courtship displays may be accompanied by growling and grunting.
name: American Flamingo

funfact: There are over 100 common names for the Northern flicker are known; these include clape, gaffer woodpecker, harry-wicket, heigh-ho, wake-up, walk-up, wick-up, yarrup, and gawker bird. Many of these names derive from attempts to imitate some of its calls.
name: Northern Flicker

funfact: The Tawny frogmouth was first described in 1801 by English naturalist John Latham. Its scientific name 'strigoides' comes from the Latin 'strix' meaning "owl" and 'oides' meaning "form".
name: Tawny Frogmouth

funfact: The genus name of the Little grebe comes from Ancient Greek takhus - "fast" and bapto - "to sink under". The specific name 'ruficollis' comes from Latin rufus - "red" and Modern Latin -collis which is translated as "-necked".
name: Little Grebe

funfact: The scientific name of the Great crested grebe comes from Latin: the genus name Podiceps is from podicis, "vent" and pes, "foot", and is a reference to the placement of a grebe's legs towards the rear of its body; the species name, cristatus, means "crested".
name: Great Crested Grebe

funfact: In 2014 the Blue-throated macaw was designated by law as a natural patrimony of Bolivia, where it is known as barba azul, which means 'blue beard' in Spanish.
name: Blue-Throated Macaw

funfact: 50 vultures can within 20 minutes reduce a sheep or impala carcass to skin and bones.
name: Scarlet macaw

funfact: A parrotâ€™s beak seems to be solid, but it is not. Like many of a parrot's bones, it is hollow, and inside it are fine bony struts which make it strong. Its outside is covered with keratin (the same substance in our fingernails). A parrotâ€™s beak grows all the time and gets worn down when the bird eats, chews wood, and grinds the top and bottom of the beak against each other.
name: Yellow-Crowned Amazon

funfact: Amazon parrots have a distinctive odor that seems to come from their respiratory system. It is not an unpleasant smell, and for those who love Amazon parrots this smell is often associated with something good. It is most noticeable close to their nares. The purpose of this smell is not known; most birds do not possess many receptors for scent.
name: Yello-Naped Amazon

funfact: At the start of each day, a group of two or three males will "scout out" potential roosting or feeding sites. They will be the first to go back to the roosting area at sunset. The "scouts" will quietly perch for about ten minutes in the tallest tree, and, once satisfied of no danger, they call loudly to the other birds, who then follow them to the site. If there is danger, the advance party will sound out with their loud signature calls, warning the group.
name: Lear's Macaw

funfact: Christopher Columbus was so impressed by the numbers of the Bahama parrot (a subspecies of the Cuban amazon) numbers when he arrived in The Bahamas in l492, that in his log he recorded, â€œFlocks of parrots darken the sunâ€.
name: Cuban Amazon

funfact: Hyacinth macaws are often considered to be gentle giants, with loving and gentle personalities.
name: Hyacinth Macaw

funfact: In its size, this bird is the second largest parrot only to the Hyacinth macaw.
name: Green-Winged Macaw

funfact: Macaws crack open buts with their strong beaks. They are also good at chewing up things in your house.
name: Blue-and-Gold Macaw

funfact: Military macaws congregate at mounds of clay along riverbanks to lick the clay to detoxify poisonous substances in their diet.
name: Military Macaw

funfact: Orange-winged amazons like oranges, mangoes and cocoa. Silent while feeding, they forage around plantations, along forest edges, and in urban areas. The only noise is the movement of leaves.
name: Orange-Winged Amazon

funfact: Red-lored amazons were first described in 1758 by Linnaeus.
name: Red-Lored Amazon

funfact: The Spixâ€™s macaw is named after the Johann Baptist von Spix, the German naturalist, who, in 1819, collected a specimen from the banks of Brazilâ€™s Rio SÃ£o Francisco in northeast Bahia. At this time, the Spixâ€™s macaw was already rare.
name: Spix's Macaw

funfact: There are about 353 different species of parrots.
name: Yellow-Headed Amazon

funfact: When raising chicks, females often perform anti-predator behavior, chasing intruders away and displaying the â€œbroken wingâ€ distraction.
name: Satin Bowerbird

funfact: American coots are the only member in the rail family truly adapted to living on the water.
name: American Coot

funfact: Black crakes sometimes perch on the backs of large mammals like hippopotami and warthogs, probably to glean parasites.
name: Black Crake

funfact: The American avocet has the popular name â€œblue shanksâ€ because of the bluish-gray color of its legs and feet.
name: American Avocet

funfact: The little goldcrest is often overlooked; however, it is surprisingly fearless, sometimes approaching within 3 m of humans during winter.
name: Goldcrest

funfact: The genus name of this species Limosa is from Latin and means "muddy", from limus, "mud". The specific lapponica refers to Lapland. The English term "godwit" was first recorded in about 1416 and is believed to imitate the bird's call.
name: Bar-Tailed Godwit

funfact: Numenius, the genus name for this species, refers to the crescent shape of its bill and is a Greek word.
name: Long-Billed Curlew

funfact: The GalÃ¡pagos penguin is the only penguin species, living on the equator.
name: GalÃ¡pagos Penguin

funfact: Fiordland penguins are extremely timid and shy animals, highly frightened by close contacts with humans; usually, their flippers and heads can be seen shivering, when humans are approaching. In general, the birds feel very nervous when outside the vegetal cover, tending to stay close to the forest.
name: Fiordland Penguin

funfact: In the Deep South of Antarctica, where these penguins live, the temperature occasionally drops as low as -60C. These birds are able to survive due to having large stores of body fat as well as several layers of scale-like feathers. In addition, during harsh weather condition, birds in colonies huddle together in order to preserve heat.
name: Emperor Penguin

funfact: Instead of constructing nests, the King penguins just carry the incubating eggs and the chicks with them, on their feet.
name: King Penguin

funfact: Snares penguins are dispersive birds. Travelling for food, they are able to migrate as far as it needs until they find a suitable foraging area. They can frequently be seen on the coasts of Stewart Island, Australia and Chatham Island, and occasionally around Tasmania.
name: Snares Penguin

funfact: The scientific name of this species is "Eudyptes schlegeli" as a commemoration of German zoologist Herman Schlegel.
name: Royal Penguin

funfact: The species is named after Alexander Von Humboldt, a German scientist, who explored South America, Cuba and Mexico in 1799.
name: Humboldt Penguin

funfact: The species is named after Philip Lutley Sclater, an English zoologist.
name: Erect-Crested Penguin

funfact: These animals are extremely shy. They spend most of the day, hiding in their burrows. During the breeding season, they hide in their nest burrows. In addition, when returning in the evening from their foraging trips, they hastily run, hiding in a temporary underground cover, where they can rest.
name: Little Blue Penguin

funfact: These animals demonstrate behavioral adaptations to high temperatures. To cool off, they usually extend their flippers upward, thus exposing more area of their body surface to a breeze. During hot days, these penguins pant like dogs. They also lose the feathers around their eyes, which grow back, when the temperature goes down.
name: Magellanic Penguin

funfact: This penguin is sometimes called a "Stonebreaker Penguin", not because it uses collects stones when building the nest, but due to emitting a loud screech, which is so shrill that could even break stones.
name: Chinstrap Penguin

funfact: Unlike other penguin species, the yellow-eyed penguin has semi-musical voice.
name: Yellow-Eyed Penguin

funfact: When on land, the penguins move around by hopping. In addition, these agile animals easily climb up rocky cliffs to get to their colonies.
name: Macaroni Penguin

funfact: When the animal dives deep into the water, the heartbeat of the penguin drops sharply from 80-100 beats per minute (bpm) to 20 bpm.
name: Gentoo Penguin

funfact: When the chick hatches, the male cares for the offspring, whereas the female makes foraging trips to feed the hatchling. In a case if the female doesn't return from the trip, the male uses "penguin's milk", which he produces from his digestive system, feeding his offspring through regurgitation.
name: Rockhopper Penguin

funfact: Owls have 14 bones in their necks; this allows the birds to rotate their necks 270 degrees. In comparison, humans have only 7.
name: Spotted Eagle-Owl

funfact: The flight of Eurasian eagle-owls is strong, direct, usually consisting of shallow wing beats and long, surprisingly fast glides. They may, unusually for owls, also soar on updrafts on rare occasions.
name: Eurasian Eagle-Owl

funfact: In poor lighting conditions, they are capable of seeing about 35 times better than humans.
name: Great Horned Owl

funfact: The ostrich is unique amongst birds in having two toes on each of its feet. All other birds possess three or four toes.
name: Ostrich

funfact: The gannets appeared about 30 million years ago. Word 'gannet' is derived from Old English ganot, meaning "strong or masculine".
name: Northern Gannet

funfact: These birds can easily be confused with the Yellow-billed cardinal or the Red-cowled cardinal, although neither of these species has the distinctive red crest, and the former clearly has a yellow bill.
name: Red-Crested Cardinal

funfact: The Australian white ibis is known as mardungurra among the Yindjibarndi people of the central and western Pilbara (a large region in the north of Western Australia).
name: Australian White Ibis

funfact: As its name suggests, the Beed hummingbird is scarcely larger than a bee. During the flight, it makes a buzzy noise, similar to a bumblebee.
name: Bee Hummingbird

funfact: The Common blackbird makes several different calls, depending on the situation. When disturbed, it gives a low, slowly repeated â€œtchucâ€, and when alarmed, it utters a shrill â€œtink-tink-tinkâ€ repeated quickly, which may become hysterical when it is faced with a dangerous predator.
name: Common Blackbird

funfact: The state bird of both Idaho and Nevada is the Mountain bluebird.
name: Mountain Bluebird

funfact: This species is the official state bird for Missouri and New York in the USA.
name: Eastern Bluebird

funfact: Western bluebirds use a range of calls to communicate. They make a mellow â€œfewâ€, which extends in brief song to â€œfew few faweeâ€. The â€œfewâ€ or â€œkewâ€ call, and the â€œche-checkâ€ calls are for location between mates during the breeding season. The defense call when there is an intruder, is a kind of â€œsquawkâ€ uttered by the male.
name: Western Bluebird

funfact: The African fish eagle is the national bird of Namibia and Zambia.
name: African Fish Eagle

funfact: These birds use three main types of vocalizations: bray, yell and haw. Meanwhile, they are sometimes called "jackass penguins" due to braying, giving out donkey-like calls.
name: African Penguin

funfact: It is suggested that the name of this unusual bird, secretary/secrÃ©taire, had been chosen because of the long quill-like feathers at the top of its neck - a reminiscent of a quill pen behind the ear of an ancient scribe.
name: Secretarybird

funfact: Great blue turacos belong to the bird family Musophagidae (literally "banana-eaters"), which includes plantain-eaters and go-away-birds. In southern Africa, both turacos and go-away-birds are commonly known as loeries.
name: Great Blue Turaco

funfact: Southern ground hornbills are a culturally pervasive and important species in southern Africa. Kruger National Park, located within South Africa, lists Southern ground hornbills as one of their â€˜Big Sixâ€™ bird species.
name: Southern Ground Hornbil

funfact: Lilac-breasted rollers get their name from their impressive courtship flight. During the breeding season, the male rises to a fair height of 69-144 meters (226-472 ft) and then descends in acrobatic swoops and dives, while uttering harsh, discordant cries.
name: Lilac-Breasted Roller

funfact: Blacksmith lapwings are named from their repeated metallic 'tink, tink, tink' alarm call, which sounds like a hammer striking an anvil.
name: Blacksmith Lapwing

funfact: African grey parrots are very smart birds. Living in the wild tropics they must learn a complex of skills. They need to learn how to differ edible food plants from toxic and how to find safe water, how to defend territory, how to avoid predators, and how to find their families if they were separated.
name: African Grey Parrot

funfact: Hand-reared Senegal parrots are one of the most popular parrots to be kept as pets. They make for a good companion and are quite friendly compared to other parrot species.
name: Senegal Parrot

funfact: The spoonbills have a global distribution; these birds are found on every continent except Antarctica.
name: African Spoonbill

funfact: Blue swallows have a musical 'bee-bee-bee-bee' call when in flight.
name: Blue Swallow

funfact: Pigeons have an acute hearing. They can hear distant storms and even volcanoes.
name: Pink Pigeon

funfact: Kiwi belong to the ratite family, which also includes the emu, ostrich, rhea, and cassowary.
name: Great Spotted Kiwi

funfact: The morepork was described by Johann Friedrich Gmelin in 1788 and was for many years considered to be the same species as the Australian boobook of mainland Australia until 1999.
name: Morepork

funfact: Some have considered that the closest relatives of Crab-plovers are the thick-knees, or the pratincoles, while others suggest they are closer to the auks and gulls.
name: Crab-Plover

funfact: Not only these penguins are top swimmers, but they also use various ways to move around while on land. Thus, they can walk with the characteristic waddling gait as well as move forward by jumping on their two feet. The Adelie penguins also toboggan or slide on their belly over the ice surface or snow.
name: Adlie Penguin

funfact: Skuas are related to gulls, waders, auks, and skimmers.
name: South Polar Skua

funfact: The Snow petrel is the only member of the genus Pagodroma, and a member of the subfamily fulmarine petrels.
name: Snow Petrel

funfact: The word 'petrel' refers to St. Peter and from the story of him walking on water, which refers to how Southern giant petrels run on top of the water as they are getting airborne.
name: Southern Giant Petrel

funfact: The bill of Indian rollers has a curved upper edge and a hooked tip and there are also long rictal bristles at the base of their bill.
name: Indian Roller

funfact: The Indian peafowl is celebrated in Hindu and Greek mythology and is the national bird of India.
name: Indian Peafowl

funfact: Painted storks have a very beautiful and elegant flight. They often make use of the late morning thermals to soar in search of foraging areas.
name: Painted Stork

funfact: The Rhinoceros hornbill is the state bird of the Malaysian state of Sarawak and the country's National Bird.
name: Rhinoceros Hornbill

funfact: The Green peafowl was an ancient symbol of the monarchs of Burma. It was also shown during British colonial times on the flag of the governor and the naval ensign, as well as on the flag of the State of Burma from 1943-1945 and on the currency of independent Burma as well.
name: Green Peafowl

funfact: During courtship displays, the head ornaments of Silver pheasants become bright in color while usually, they are duller and reduced.
name: Silver Pheasant

funfact: The Milky stork has long thick toes that probably serve to increase the surface area of its feet and therefore reduce pressure from standing and walking on the soft mud of its foraging area; this way the bird does not sink considerably when foraging and feeding.
name: Milky Stork

funfact: The Crested ibis is one of the worldâ€™s most threatened ibis species.
name: Crested Ibis

funfact: The genus name of the Golden pheasant comes from Ancient Greek 'khrusolophos' which means 'with golden crest', and 'pictus' which comes from Latin for 'painted' and 'pingere' - 'to paint'.
name: Golden Pheasant

funfact: The Japanese quail was first considered a subspecies of the  Common quail, and in 1983, it was distinguished as its own species.
name: Japanese Quail

funfact: The Bali myna was discovered in 1910, and in 1991 was designated the faunal emblem of Bali.
name: Bali Myna

funfact: The generic name of the Black stilt 'Himantopus' comes from the Ancient Greek and means 'strap-leg'.
name: Black Stilt

funfact: The range of the Common myna is increasing at such a rapid rate that in 2000 this species was declared as one of the world's most invasive species and one of only three birds in the top 100 species that pose an impact on biodiversity, agriculture and human interests.
name: Common Myna

funfact: The Nicobar pigeon is the largest living pigeon in the world.
name: Nicobar Pigeon

funfact: Although many people believe the Tawny owl has exceptional night vision, its retina is no more sensitive than a human's; in fact, the key to its successful hunting are asymmetrically placed ears which give the owl excellent directional hearing.
name: Tawny Owl

funfact: The scientific name of the Common swift 'Apus' is Latin for a 'swift', thought by the ancients to be a type of swallow with no feet (from Ancient Greek Î±, a, "without", and Ï€Î¿ÏÏ‚, pous, "foot").
name: Common Swift

funfact: The European roller is very similar in appearance and behavior to the Abyssinian roller, which appears to be its closest relative.
name: European Roller

funfact: The Little owl is closely associated with the Greek goddess Athena and the Roman goddess Minerva and hence represents wisdom and knowledge.
name: Little Owl

funfact: The scientific name of the Common pheasant 'colchicus' is Latin for 'of Colchis' (modern-day Georgia), a country on the Black Sea where these birds became known to Europeans.
name: Common Pheasant

funfact: The name 'mor-hen' has been recorded in English since the 13th century. The word 'moor' here is an old sense meaning marsh, however, these birds are not usually found in moorland.
name: Common Moorhen

funfact: Owls belong to the genus 'Asio' are known as the eared owls, as they have tufts of feathers resembling mammalian ears. These "ear" tufts may or may not be visible.
name: Short-Eared Owl

funfact: The Montaguâ€™s harrier was named after the British naturalist George Montagu.
name: Montagu's Harrier

funfact: Golden orioles use whistles to communicate with each other but when they want to inform nearby birds about potential predators they will produce harsh, alarm calls.
name: Golden Oriole

funfact: The scientific name of the Grey partridge is the Latin for 'partridge', and is itself derived from Ancient Greek word 'perdix'.
name: Grey Partridge

funfact: The name of the Northern shoveler is derived from its highly specialized bill that is used to forage for aquatic invertebrates.
name: Northern Shoveler

funfact: The Ural owl is a member of the 'Strix' genus, which are quite often referred to as wood owls.
name: Ural Owl

funfact: The scientific name of the Common snipe, 'gallinago' is New Latin for a woodcock or snipe from Latin 'gallina' (a hen) and the suffix '-ago' (resembling).
name: Common Snipe

funfact: The House sparrow is the most widely distributed wild bird.
name: House Sparrow

funfact: The Long-eared owl has relatively large ear slits placed asymmetrically on the sides of its head; the left ear is placed higher and right lower which allows the birds to absorb sound both from above and below. Due to its ear structure, the hearing of a Long-eared owl is around ten times better than humans.
name: Long-Eared Owl

funfact: The Barn swallow is the national bird of Austria and Estonia.
name: Barn Swallow

funfact: The osprey is unusual in that it is a single living species that occurs nearly worldwide.
name: Osprey

funfact: The Red knot performs one of the longest migrations of any bird. Every year it travels more than 9,000 mi (14,000 km) from the Arctic to the southern tip of South America.
name: Red Knot

funfact: Common starlings on migration can fly at 60-80 km/h (37-50 mph) and cover up to 1,000-1,500 km (620-930 mi).
name: Common Starling

funfact: The genus name of the hen harrier 'Circus' comes from Ancient Greek 'kirkos' and means 'circle' which refers to a bird of prey named for its circling flight. The specific name 'cyaneus' is Latin and means 'dark-blue'.
name: Hen Harrier

funfact: Nightingales are so named because they frequently sing at night. The name has been used for more than 1,000 years, being highly recognisable even in its Old English form nihtegale, which means "night songstress". This is why its name includes "night" in several languages. Early writers assumed the female sang when it is, in fact, the male.
name: Nightingale

funfact: The genus name of the Great snipe Gallinago is New Latin for a woodcock or snipe from Latin 'gallina' (a hen) and the suffix '-ago' (resembling). The specific 'media' is Latin and means 'intermediate' because the Great snipe is intermediate in size between the woodcock and the Common snipe.
name: Great Snipe

funfact: The scientific name of the Tufted duck is derived from Ancient Greek 'aithuia' an unidentified seabird mentioned by authors including Hesychius and Aristotle, and Latin, fuligo "soot" and gula "throat".
name: Tufted Duck

funfact: Kiwi are the national symbol of New Zealand.
name: Okarito Kiwi

funfact: The kiwiâ€™s plumage looks almost like hair; this is due to the loose structure of the feathers, which do not lock together as in other birds.
name: Southern Brown Kiwi

funfact: The scientific name of the Ring-necked duck is derived from Greek 'aithuia' an unidentified seabird mentioned by authors including Hesychius and Aristotle, and Latin 'collaris', 'of the neck' from collum, 'neck'.
name: Ring-Necked Duck

funfact: During the nesting period and when raising their young Clapper rails often use a â€œbroken wingâ€ display in order to distract predators and take them away from nests.
name: Clapper Rail

funfact: The former Latin name of the Scissor-tailed flycatcher was 'Muscivora forficata'. The name, Muscivora, comes from the Latin word (musca) which means "fly" and (vorare) - "to devour"; the name forficata comes from the Latin word (forfex) which means "scissors".
name: Scissor-Tailed Flycatcher

funfact: The Northern mockingbird is known for its intelligence. A 2009 study showed that the bird was able to recognize individual humans, particularly noting those who had previously been intruders or threats. Also, these birds recognize their breeding spots and return to areas in which they had the greatest success in previous years.
name: Northern Mockingbird

funfact: Of all hummingbirds in the United States, the Ruby-throated hummingbird has the largest breeding range.
name: Ruby-Throated Hummingbird

funfact: The genus name of the Ruddy duck comes from Ancient Greek 'oxus', which means 'sharp', and 'oura' which means 'tail', and 'jamaicensis' is 'from Jamaica'.
name: Ruddy Duck

funfact: The Steller's jay is the only crested jay found west of the Rocky Mountains.
name: Steller's Jay

funfact: Grasshopper sparrows get their common name for the insect-like song and they are one of the few sparrow species that sings 2 different songs; one song is performed by males to attract the female and another to defend a breeding territory.
name: Grasshopper Sparrow

funfact: The Brown thrasher is the state bird of Georgia.
name: Brown Thrasher

funfact: Song sparrows are most easily confused with Lincoln's sparrow and the Savannah sparrow. The former can be recognized by its shorter, grayer tail and the differently-patterned head, the brown cheeks forming a clear-cut angular patch. The Savannah sparrow has a forked tail and yellowish flecks on the face when seen up close.
name: Song Sparrow

funfact: Woodpeckers are found worldwide, except for Australia, New Guinea, New Zealand, Madagascar, and the extreme polar regions.
name: Yellow-Bellied Sapsucker

funfact: The Flammulated owl was first discovered in 1852.
name: Flammulated Owl

funfact: The Turquoise-browed motmot is a well-known bird in its range and has been chosen as the national bird of both El Salvador and Nicaragua. It has acquired a number of local names including guardabarranco ("ravine-guard") in Nicaragua, Torogoz in El Salvador (based on its call) and pÃ¡jaro reloj ("clock bird") in the YucatÃ¡n, based on its habit of wagging its tail like a pendulum. In Costa Rica, this bird is known as momoto cejiceleste or the far-less flattering pÃ¡jaro bobo ("foolish bird"), owing to its tendency to allow humans to come very near it without flying away.
name: Turquoise-Browed Motmot

funfact: The Resplendent quetzal is the national bird of Guatemala, and its image is found on the country's flag and coat of arms. It also lends its name to the country's currency, the Guatemalan quetzal (abbreviation GTQ).
name: Resplendent Quetzal

funfact: Saw-whet owls are one of the smallest owl species in North America.
name: Northern Saw-When Owl

funfact: The Latin name of the Lesser roadrunner means "swift earth-cuckoo".
name: Lesser Roadrunner

funfact: Screech owls are the smallest owls that are found in North America.
name: Whiskered Screech Owl

funfact: Until the 1980s, Western and Eastern screech-owls were considered to be the same species because they are very similar in appearance; however, they have different calls and it is thought that they can recognize their own kind by sound.
name: Western Screech Owl

funfact: The common name 'tui' comes from the MÄori language.
name: Tui

funfact: The genus name of the Hooded merganser 'Lophodytes' comes from the Greek language where 'lophos' means 'crest', and 'dutes' - is 'diver'.
name: Hooded Merganser

funfact: White-crowned sparrows are known for their natural alertness mechanism, which allows them to stay awake for up to 2 weeks during migration. This effect has been studied for possible human applications, such as shift-work drowsiness or truck driving.
name: White-Crowned Sparrow

funfact: The genus name 'Sayornis' is constructed from the specific part of Charles Lucien Bonaparte's name for Say's phoebe, Muscicapa saya, and Ancient Greek 'ornis' which means 'bird'. The word 'Phoebe' is an alternative name for the Roman moon-goddess Diana, but it may also have been chosen to imitate the bird's call.
name: Eastern Phoebe

funfact: The name of the Piping plover is derived from its plaintive bell-like whistles which are often heard before the bird is visible.
name: Piping Plover

funfact: Although they share the name sparrow, American sparrows are more closely related to Old World buntings than they are to the Old World sparrows (true sparrows). American sparrows are also similar in both appearance and habits to finches.
name: Savannah Sparrow

funfact: The American robin is the state bird of Connecticut, Michigan, and Wisconsin.
name: American Robin

funfact: Chipping sparrows belong to a group of mainly New World passerine birds called American sparrows. Although they share the name sparrow, American sparrows are more closely related to Old World buntings than they are to the Old World sparrows. American sparrows are also similar in both appearance and habit to finches, with which they sometimes used to be classified.
name: Chipping Sparrow

funfact: The Tufted puffin was first described in 1769 by German zoologist Peter Simon Pallas.
name: Tufted Puffin

funfact: The Spectacled eider was first described in 1847 by the German scientist Johann Fischer von Waldheim.
name: Spectacled Eider

funfact: The word 'junco' is the Spanish for 'rush', from Latin 'juncus'. Its modern scientific name means "winter junco", from Latin 'hyemalis' which is translated as 'of the winter'.
name: Dark-Eyed Junco

funfact: Gray jays can mimic other birds, especially predators such as Red-tailed hawks, Broad-winged hawks, and merlins.
name: Gray Jay

funfact: The common English name 'shrike' comes from Old English 'scrÄ«c', alluding to the bird's shriek-like call.
name: Loggerhead Shrike

funfact: California quail was established as the state bird of California in 1932.
name: California Quail

funfact: The Western grebe is the largest among North American grebes.
name: Western Grebe

funfact: Spotted owls have blackish-brown eyes while most owls have yellow or red-orange eyes.
name: Spotted Owl

funfact: The Barred owl is the only true owl of the eastern United States which has brown eyes; all others have yellow eyes.
name: Barred Owl

funfact: The Eastern screech owl's plumage ranges in color from gray to brown and to even red or rufous. Even owlets from the same nest may be of a different color. While the gray morph provides remarkably effective camouflage amongst the bark of hardwood trees, red morphs may find security in certain pine trees and the colorful leaves of changing deciduous trees.
name: Eastern Screech Owl

funfact: The word â€œpygmyâ€ in the name of the bird means "small". Being only 15-17 cm tall, this tiny owl is one of the smallest in North America. However, despite its size, the Northern pygmy owl is fierce and doesn't hesitate to prey on birds and mammals larger than itself.
name: Northern Pygmy Owl

funfact: Anna's hummingbird was named after a French courtier Anna MassÃ©na, Duchess of Rivoli.
name: Anna's Hummingbird

funfact: Black-chinned hummingbirds are often mistaken for Anna's, Lucifer, broad-tailed, and Costa's hummingbirds as they often hybridize with these birds.
name: Black-Chinned Hummingbird

funfact: Contrary to its name, the California gull is the state bird of Utah.
name: California Gull

funfact: The name of this curious and intelligent bird is derived from Ancient Greek rhynchos ("beak") and psittakos ("parrot") and Greek pachy- ("thick") and rhynchos ("beak"), hence a "thick-beaked parrot".
name: Thick-Billed Parrot

funfact: The scientific name of the Great roadrunner means "Californian earth-cuckoo".
name: Greater Roadrunner

funfact: The Blue-crowned motmot's tail is often called "racket"-like. In fact the feathers don't grow in that way it is the bird prunes them down to create this distinctive shape.
name: Blue-Crowned Motmot

funfact: Many refer to scrub-jays as "blue jays", however, the blue jay is completely a different species of bird.
name: Western Scrub-Jay

funfact: The word plover came from a Latin 'pluvia' which means 'rain'. In Medieval England, some migratory birds became known as plovers because they returned to their breeding grounds each spring with rain.
name: Mountain Plover

funfact: Western gulls take approximately four years to reach their full plumage, their layer of feathers and the patterns and colors on the feathers.
name: Western Gull

funfact: The Northern brown kiwi is the only species of kiwi found internationally in zoos.
name: Northern Brown Kiwi

funfact: The Henslow's sparrow was named by John James Audubon in honor of John Stevens Henslow (a British priest, botanist, and geologist).
name: Henslow's Sparrow

funfact: The Carolina parakeet was the only indigenous parrot within its range, as well as one of only two parrots native to the United States. The other one is the Thick-billed parrot.
name: Carolina Parakeet

funfact: The Sprague's pipit was named by John James Audubon (American ornithologist, naturalist, and painter) for Isaac Sprague; he was an artist who accompanied J. J. Audubon on his trip up the Missouri River.
name: Sprague's Pipit

funfact: The Mountain quail is the largest of all quail species that are found in the United States.
name: Mountain Quail

funfact: Rufous hummingbirds nest further north (Alaska) than any other hummingbird.
name: Rufous Hummingbird

funfact: The Calliope hummingbird was named after the Greek muse of eloquence and epic poetry Calliope.
name: Calliope Hummingbird

funfact: The Lesser prairie chicken was first described in 1873 by Robert Ridgway who was an American ornithologist.
name: Lesser Prairie Chicken

funfact: The Elf owl is the world's lightest owl and it is also the world's smallest owl.
name: Elf Owl

funfact: Greater prairie chickens are not afraid of severe winter weather. When the snow is thick they "dive" into the snow to keep warm.
name: Greater Prairie Chicken

funfact: The Florida scrub-jay is known to have been present in Florida as a distinct species for at least 2 million years and is possibly derived from the ancestors of Woodhouse's scrub-jay.
name: Florida Scrub-Jay

funfact: Apart from its greater size, the Common raven differs from its cousins, the crows, by having a larger and heavier black beak, shaggy feathers around the throat and above the beak, and a wedge-shaped tail. Despite their bulk, ravens are easily as agile in flight as their smaller cousins. In flight the feathers produce a creaking sound that has been likened to the rustle of silk.
name: Common Raven

funfact: The specific name of the Horned lark 'alpestris' comes from Latin and means 'of the high mountains', from Alpes, the Alps.
name: Horned Lark

funfact: Merlins were once known as the â€œPigeon hawkâ€ in North America because they resemble a pigeon in flight.
name: Merlin

funfact: Common mergansers are often known as "sawbills" due to serrated edges to their bills that help the birds grip their prey.
name: Common Merganser

funfact: Due to the striking appearance, large colorful bill, waddling gait, and their behavior Atlantic puffins have been given a number of endearing names including "clowns of the sea" and "sea parrots", and juvenile puffins may be called "pufflings".
name: Atlantic Puffin

funfact: The Northern goshawk is the only raptor in its genus found in both Eurasia and North America.
name: Northern Goshawk

funfact: In Europe, the Boreal owl is known as Tengmalm's owl after Swedish naturalist Peter Gustaf Tengmalm or, more rarely, Richardson's owl after Sir John Richardson.
name: Boreal Owl

funfact: The scientific name of the Long-tailed duck is derived from Latin clangere, "to resound", and hyemalis, "of winter".
name: Long-Tailed Duck

funfact: The Willow ptarmigan's scientific name, Lagopus lagopus comes from Ancient Greek lagos (Î»Î±Î³Ï‰Ï‚) 'hare' and pous (Ï€Î¿Ï…Ï‚) 'foot', in reference to the bird's feathered feet which allow it to stay warm on the frozen ground.
name: Willow Ptarmigan

funfact: The Common loon is the provincial bird of Ontario, and it appears on Canadian currency, including the one-dollar "loonie" coin and a previous series of $20 bills.
name: Common Loon

funfact: The scientific name of the Pink-gooted goose comes from the ancient Greek brachus "short" and rhunchos "bill".
name: Pink-Footed Goose

funfact: The Harlequin duck takes its name from Harlequin (French Arlequin, Italian Arlecchino), a colorfully dressed character in Commedia dell'arte. The scientific name 'Histrionicus histrionicus' comes from the Latin word "histrio", "actor".
name: Harlequin Duck

funfact: The scientific name of the Northen fulmsr "Fulmarus glacialis" can be broken down to the Old Norse word full meaning "foul" and mar meaning "gull". "Foul-gull" is in reference to its stomach oil and also its superficial similarity to seagulls. Finally, glacialis is translated from Latin as "glacial" because of its extreme northern range.
name: Northern Fulmar

funfact: The Snowy owl is the official bird of Quebec, Canada.
name: Snowy Owl

funfact: Barnacle geese belong to the genus Branta of black geese; this genus contains species with largely black plumage which distinguishes them from the grey Anser species.
name: Barnacle Goose

funfact: The scientific name of this bird, Fratercula corniculata, comes from the Medieval Latin 'fratercula' and means 'friar'; this is due to their black-and-white plumage which resembles the robes of monks. The name 'corniculata' means 'horn-shaped' or 'crescent-shaped', in reference to the black horn above the bird's eye.
name: Horned Puffin

funfact: Northern hawk-owls have exceptional hearing and can plunge into the snow to capture rodents below the surface.
name: Northern Hawk-Owl

funfact: The scientific name of the Ivory gull â€˜Pagophilaâ€™ means  "sea-ice-loving" and â€˜Eburneaâ€™ means â€œivory-colored.â€
name: Ivory Gull

funfact: The genus name of this species comes from Latin and means 'relating to rain' from 'pluvia' (rain). It was believed that golden plovers flocked when rain was imminent. The species name 'fulva' refers to the tawny color of the bird.
name: Pacific Golden Plover

funfact: The scientific name of the Sand martin, Riparia, is derived from the Latin 'ripa' and means 'riverbank'.
name: Sand Martin

funfact: The scientific name of the Glossy ibis comes from Ancient Greek plegados and Latin, falcis, both meaning "sickle" and referring to its distinctive shape of the bill.
name: Glossy Ibis

funfact: American kestrels have two black spots (ocelli) on each side of their nape. The function of these spots is debated, but the most commonly accepted theory is that they act as "false eyes", and help to protect kestrels from potential attackers.
name: American Kestrel

funfact: Originally the American oystercatcher was called the "sea pie". It was renamed in 1731 when naturalist Mark Catesby observed this bird eating oysters.
name: American Oystercatcher

funfact: The specific name of the Purple gallinule 'martinica' denotes "of Martinique", an insular region of France located in the eastern Caribbean Sea.
name: Purple Gallinule

funfact: The genus name of the Laughing gull "Leucophaeus" comes from Ancient Greek leukos - "white", and phaios - "dusky". The specific name "atricilla" comes from Latin ater - "black", and cilla - "tail".
name: Laughing Gull

funfact: Broad-winged hawks were named for their short but broad wings.
name: Broad-Winged Hawk

funfact: The Cinnamon teal is considered one of the most beautiful ducks in the Americas.
name: Cinnamon Teal

funfact: Eastern kingbirds belong to tyrant flycatcher, a family of passerine birds that are found only throughout North and South America.
name: Eastern Kingbird

funfact: Male Sharp-shinned hawks are the smallest hawks in the United States and Canada.
name: Sharp-Shinned Hawk

funfact: Swainson's hawk was named after William Swainson, a British naturalist.
name: Swainson's Hawk

funfact: Aplomado is an unusual Spanish word for "lead-colored", referring to the blue-grey areas of the plumage - an approximate English translation would be "plumbeous falcon".
name: Aplomado Falcon

funfact: Ferruginous pygmy owls belong to the large family known as typical owls. This family contains most species of owls.
name: Ferruginous Pygmy Owl

funfact: John James Audubon gave Harris's hawk its English name in honor of his ornithological companion, financial supporter, and friend Edward Harris.
name: Harris's Hawk

funfact: Blue grosbeaks belong to the same family as the northern cardinal, "tropical" or New World buntings, and "cardinal-grosbeaks" or New World grosbeaks.
name: Blue Grosbeak

funfact: To protect their chicks, Snowy plovers use displays to distract predators away from their chicks; they may also use specific calls to signal the young to hide.
name: Snowy Plover

funfact: Acadian flycatchers are very difficult to see, but they are easily detected due to their unique "ka-zeep" song.
name: Acadian Flycatcher

funfact: The scientific name of the Northern pintail comes from two Latin words: anas, meaning "duck", and acuta, which comes from the verb acuere, "to sharpen"; both the species term and the English name, refer to the pointed tail of the male in breeding plumage.
name: Northern Pintail

funfact: Hawks have excellent eyesight and are able to see different colors.
name: White Hawk

funfact: Green jays that occur in South America are often treated as a separate species; they are known as Inca jays.
name: Green Jay

funfact: Eastern meadowlarks are not larks, they are related to orioles and blackbirds.
name: Eastern Meadowlark

funfact: The Clay-color robin is the national bird of Costa Rica, where it is well known as the yigÃ¼irro (Spanish: [Êi'É£wiro]).
name: Clay-Colored Robin

funfact: The scientific name of the Swallow-tailed kite comes from Ancient Greek where elanos is translated as "kite" and -oides means "resembling".
name: Swallow-Tailed Kite

funfact: Hummingbirds have good memories and always remember where good feeding areas are.
name: Broad-Tailed Hummingbird

funfact: The Pied-billed grebe is the only grebe on record to have visited the Galapagos Islands.
name: Pied-Billed Grebe

funfact: Male and female Burrowing owls are similar in size and appearance. Males, however, appear lighter in color than females because they spend more time outside the burrow during daylight, and their feathers become "sun-bleached".
name: Burrowing Owl

funfact: To walk through dense vegetation, Virginia rails have evolved a laterally compressed body and strong forehead feathers adapted to withstand wear from pushing through vegetation.
name: Virginia Rail

funfact: The genus name of the Blachburnian warbler 'Setophaga' comes from Ancient Greek 'ses (moth), and 'phagos' (eating), and the specific 'fusca' is Latin for brown.
name: Blackburnian Warbler

funfact: The common English name "kakapo" comes from the MÄori "kÄkÄpÅ" where "kÄkÄ"  is "parrot" and "pÅ" - "night".
name: Kakapo

funfact: The common name kea comes from MÄori, probably for the sound of their in-flight call - â€˜keee aaaâ€™.
name: Kea

funfact: The genus name of the American golden plover comes from Latin and means 'relating to rain', from pluvia, 'rain'. It was believed that golden plovers flocked when rain was imminent. Their name 'dominica' refers to Santo Domingo, now Hispaniola (an island in the Caribbean archipelago), in the West Indies.
name: American Golden Plover

funfact: The name 'redstart' refers to the male's red tail, where 'start' is an old word for tail.
name: American Redstart

funfact: It is suggested that the name "Sora" is probably taken from a Native American language.
name: Sora

funfact: The genus name of the Spotted sandpiper 'Actitis' comes from Ancient Greek 'aktites' and means 'coast-dweller'.
name: Spotted Sandpiper

funfact: The common name of the Chimney swift refers to its preferred nesting site and its speedy flight.
name: Chimney Swift

funfact: The current genus name of the Purple martin refers to Procne (Î ÏÏŒÎºÎ½Î·), a mythological girl who was turned into a swallow to save her from her husband. The word 'subis' is Latin and refers to a type of bird that breaks eaglesâ€™ eggs; it may have been applied to Purple martins because of their aggression towards birds of prey when martins are nesting.
name: Purple Martin

funfact: The Baltimore oriole is the state bird of Maryland. It is also the inspiration for the Baltimore Orioles baseball team.
name: Baltimore Oriole

funfact: The Snail kite belongs to the same family which also includes the eagles, hawks, and Old World vultures.
name: Snail Kite

funfact: White-tailed kites have a gull-like coloration but in flight, these birds look like falcons.
name: White-Tailed Kite

funfact: The genus name of this species 'Rynchops' comes from the Ancient Greek rhunkhos 'bill' and ops 'face'. The specific 'niger' is the Latin word and is translated as 'black'.
name: Black Skimmer

funfact: Spoonbills are found on every continent except Antarctica.
name: Roseate Spoonbill

funfact: The Vermilion flycatcher was first described in 1783 by Pieter Boddaert who was a Dutch naturalist and physician.
name: Vermilion Flycatcher

funfact: Zebra finches are the most popular cage bird for more than 100 years!
name: Zebra Finch

funfact: Australian magpies are described as one of Australia's most accomplished songbirds. They have an array of complex vocalizations and can mimic over 35 species of native and introduced birds, as well as dogs and horses. Magpies can even mimic human speech when living in close proximity to humans.
name: Australian Magpie

funfact: The name of the Magpie-lark comes from the Ancient Greek words cyanos "dark blue" and leukos "white" despite the black and white plumage. However, there can be a bluish sheen to the black back of a bird.
name: Magpie-lark

funfact: Barking owls enjoy bathing early in the morning.
name: Barking Owl

funfact: The Victoria crowned pigeon is the largest species of pigeon in the world.
name: Victoria Crowned Pigeon

funfact: Powerful owls usually use several perches that may be occupied intermittently for years at a time.
name: Powerful Owl

funfact: The Australian raven is also known as the southern raven, southern crow, and Kelly. It was also called 'wugan' by the local Eora and Darug inhabitants of the Sydney Basin.
name: Australian Raven

funfact: The Red-browed finch was first described by the English ornithologist John Latham in 1801.
name: Red-Browed Finch

funfact: The Black-shouldered kite is often confused with its close relative Letter-winged kite in Australia; the latter can be distinguished by the striking black markings under its wings.
name: Black-Shouldered Kite

funfact: The name of these birds originates from the type of habitat that they live in. Mallee is a certain eucalypt species and is the dominant vegetation throughout the semiarid areas of Australia.
name: Malleefowl

funfact: In MÄori, the Brown teal is known as PÄteke. The use of the name 'Pateke' is now common and is specific for this particular species.
name: Brown Teal

funfact: The Little spotted kiwi is the smallest species of all 5 kiwis.
name: Little Spotted Kiwi

funfact: Owls rarely drink water because they get most of the hydration from the prey they feed on.
name: Striped Owl

funfact: In Brazil, Spectacled owls are known locally as "knocking owls".
name: Spectacled Owl

funfact: The Scarlet ibis is one of the two national birds of Trinidad and Tobago.
name: Scarlet Ibis

funfact: Blue-headed parrots often visit clay banks along rivers as they require minerals to neutralize toxins contained in the seeds that parrots consume in their diet.
name: Blue-Headed Parrot

funfact: The Great green macaw belongs to the genus Ara, which includes other large parrots, such as the Scarlet macaw, the Military macaw, and the Blue-and-yellow macaw.
name: Great Green Macaw

funfact: Nanday parakeets may fall asleep on their back with their feet sticking straight up in the air looking as if they are playing dead.
name: Nanday Parakeet

funfact: The genus name of the Monk parakeet combines the Ancient Greek 'mus, muos' meaning 'mouse' and the New Latin 'psitta' meaning 'parrot', alluding to the mouse-grey face and underparts. The specific epithet 'monachus' comes from Late Latin and means a "monk".
name: Monk Parakeet
